"# Appendix Z ‚Äî The whole book in one page

A summary you can keep on your desk.

## The thesis

A scalar is a lie you tell yourself to make the code shorter. Every value in a program carries meaning beyond its digits: kind, unit, provenance, range, precision. Programs that respect this discipline are honest; programs that ignore it are quietly wrong in ways that show up months later.

## The rules

1. **Every value has a kind.** Money, time, distance, temperature, percent, rate, id ‚Äî each is its own kind, not a plain number.
2. **Every value carries its unit.** Meters vs feet. Dollars vs euros. Celsius vs Fahrenheit. The unit is not decoration.
3. **Every value has provenance.** Where did this number come from ‚Äî user input, sensor, computed, default? The answer matters when the value is wrong.
4. **Every operation checks kinds.** Mixed-kind operations refuse or convert explicitly, never silently.
5. **Every value is validated at the boundary.** Untrusted inputs become typed values at the door. The middle of the program only sees typed values.
6. **Every value is displayed only at the exit.** Formatting happens at the last moment, not the middle.

## The types

- `money` ‚Äî `(money :amount N :currency SYM :scale S :provenance P)`
- `distance` ‚Äî `(distance :meters N :precision P)`
- `temperature` ‚Äî `(temperature :fahrenheit N)` or `(temperature :celsius N)`
- `time-instant` ‚Äî `(instant N)` (seconds since Unix epoch)
- `time-duration` ‚Äî `(duration N)` (seconds)
- `time-local` ‚Äî `(local-datetime Y M D H M S :zone Z)`
- `time-calendar` ‚Äî `(calendar-date Y M D)`
- `percent` ‚Äî `(percent V :of B)` (value of base)
- `ratio` ‚Äî `(ratio N D)`
- `rate` ‚Äî `(rate Q :per P :unit U)`
- `color` ‚Äî `(color :rgb (R G B))`
- `vector` ‚Äî `(vector :dim (X Y ...))`
- `matrix` ‚Äî `(matrix rows cols :entries ...)`
- `optional` ‚Äî `(optional/some V)` `(optional/none)` `(optional/absent :reason R)` `(optional/unknown)`
- `result` ‚Äî `(result/ok V)` `(result/error SYM :ctx C)`

## The verbs

- `validate-KIND` ‚Äî turn raw input into a typed value or a descriptive error.
- `KIND-eq?`, `KIND<`, `KIND>` ‚Äî kind-aware comparisons.
- `KIND/add`, `KIND/subtract`, `KIND/scale` ‚Äî kind-aware arithmetic.
- `KIND/convert :to UNIT` ‚Äî explicit unit conversion.
- `KIND/render :locale L :precision P` ‚Äî kind-aware display.
- `KIND/from-string`, `KIND/to-string` ‚Äî round-trip parsing.
- `KIND/mean`, `KIND/sum`, `KIND/median` ‚Äî kind-aware statistics.

## The pattern

```
raw input ‚Üí validate ‚Üí typed value ‚Üí operate ‚Üí typed result ‚Üí render ‚Üí display
   ‚Üë                                                                        ‚Üë
   boundary                                                          boundary
```

Validation at one boundary, rendering at the other. The middle is typed all the way through.

